    "response": "Hello Watanabe-san! I'm glad you're having a fruitful experience in your paddy-rice farming. To achieve maximum yield, follow these best practices:  1. Start with a balanced soil formula. For each layer of soil, add 5 parts nitrogen, 3 parts phosphorus, and 2 parts potassium per every 20 liters of water used.   2. Monitor soil moisture levels to ensure proper drainage. With 22°C and sunlight, you should begin draining gradually to dry the grains. If rain is forecast, harvest early.  3. Nitrogen is low (12), which is normal—don't add more. Potassium and phosphorus are stable, supporting grain filling. The first five days of planting should be monitored regularly, as they may affect the yield. When necessary, boost nitrogen or potassium levels to support better grain growth. In the past, harvesting was early to maintain a consistent yield. If you haven't observed this pattern yet, adjust your practices accordingly. 4. Dry grains gradually to 14% for storage—great work so far! 5. Harvest them before ripe, or they might mature too soon. The optimal time for harvest is when the water content in the grains reaches 20%. With proper soil management practices and patience, you should achieve a great yield."
}
